>"This is a bAdkOde script.\n";
>"The interpreter was created in Java by Vivin Suresh Paliath.\n\n";
>"This interpreter, as of now, supports:\n\n";
>"1. The Print statement with all escape characters and concatenation.\n";
>"2. Creation (with casting) and Printing of variables.\n";
>"3. Input into variables (defined or undefined).\n\n";

>"The Print statement in bAdkOde takes the following form:\n\n";
>">{String to Print};\n\n";
>"An example is:\n\n";
>">\"Goodbye Cruel World!\";\n\n";
>"Now the torture test for the print statement!\n\n";

>"\\\\\\\"\"" + "\\\\\"+++;;;;\";\";\"+\"+\\;\\;\\;\\+\\+\\+\"\"\"\\\\\"" + "\n";

>"Press Enter to continue...";
<pause;

>"The syntax for creating variables in bAdkOde is the same as C, C++ or Java.\n\n";
>"Examples of variable declaration in bAdkOde are:\n\n";
>"char charVar = 'c';\n";
>"int intVar = 5;\n";
>"float floatVar = 4.5;\n";
>"double doubleVar = 3.141592654;\n\n";
>"To prove that it works, have a look at this output:\n\n";

char charVar = 'c';
int intVar = 5;
float floatVar = 4.5;
double doubleVar = 3.141592654;

>"charVar is of type char and has value " + charVar + "\n";
>"intVar is of type int and has value " + intVar + "\n";
>"floatVar is of type float and has value " + floatVar + "\n";
>"doubleVar is of type float and has value " + doubleVar + "\n\n";
>"\n\n\n\n";

>"Press Enter to continue...";
<pause;

>"Explicit casting is also supported. Examples are:\n\n";

>"int icfDouble = (int) 55.324;\n";
>"char ccfDouble = (char) 65.002;\n\n";

char ccfDouble = (char) 65.002;
int icfDouble = (int) 55.324;

double oriDouble = 55.324;
double orcDouble = 65.002;

>"The results of casting:\n\n";
>"Original double value: " + oriDouble + "\n";
>"Double casted to int value: " + icfDouble + "\n";
>"\nOriginal double value: " + orcDouble + "\n";
>"Double casted to char value: " + ccfDouble + "\n\n";

>"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n";

>"Press Enter to continue...";
<pause;

>"The Input statement in bAdkOde takes the following form:\n\n";
>"<{variable name};\n\n";
>"An example is:\n\n";
>"<number;\n\n";

>"Try this out...\n\n";

int num1;
int num2;

>"Enter a number:";
<num1;

>"Enter another number:";
<num2;

>"The numbers entered were " + num1 + " and " + num2 + ".\n\n";
>"bAdkOde will also accept input for an undefined variable.\n";
>"For example, if you assume in the previous example that the variable \"number\"\n";
>"wasn't defined, and you entered some value, this variable is automatically\ncreated and is assigned a type based on the Input entered.\n\n";
>"For example, enter some values for the following (of different types):\n\n";

>"Enter something:";
<something;
>"Enter something else:";
<somethingelse;

>"I will now terminate the script with an error. You should see the variables\nin the symbol table with types based on the input you entered.\n";
>"The variable names are something (the first prompt) and somethingelse (the\nsecond prompt).\n";
<pause;
q

